<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-483-096  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 483 096.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  July 31 1989 v6 n30 p29(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Threat of viruses must be taken seriously. (computer viruses)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Zalubski, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Information security currently receives unprecedented attention.andO;Many vendors are offering data encryption schemes, cryptographicequipment and access control devices.andP;  These developments, thoughwelcome, do not attack the root of the problem, theless-than-casual attention security matters receive from users andmanagement.andP;  Many users see security procedures, such as changingpasswords, an inconvenient chores that prevent them fromcompleting their work in a timely and efficient manner.andP;  Usersmust also employ the 'need-to-know' principle' when transmittingdata to others.andP;  Many are unfortunately casual about thisprinciple as well.andP;  Computer crime accounts for losses of $5billion per year for businesses.andP;  Much of that results fromsupposedly harmless information exchanges.andP;  Network securitymanagers must be properly and thoroughly trained and supported bymanagement in their efforts to secure network data, in order tocombat this problem.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer VirusesSecurityNetworksEncryptionPasswordsAccess ControlsAccess RightsUser Interface.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>